title: Grateful Dead Live at Boston Garden on 1994-09-29

description:
Set 1

Hell In A Bucket, Peggy-O, Wang Dang Doodle, Ramble On Rose, When I Paint My Masterpiece*, Brown Eyed Women, Let It Grow

Set 2

Playin' In The Band- > Eyes Of The World-> Estimated Prophet-> He's Gone-> Drums-> Space-> Spanish Jam-> The Other One-> Wharf Rat-> Sugar Magnolia, E: I Fought the Law

* Weir on acoustic guitar

reviews.review_text: Thank You From the Bottom of My Heart to the Height of My Soul Sometimes it's hard to even consider listening to anything 94 or 95 without feeling so sad.  But this show is a sheer celebration of everything the Dead are good at, and a complete listening/dancing/gardening pleasure.

Gahden gold In  the early 1990's the advent of HQ FOB sourced tapes became more and more available, even if it was still a  big no no with the band. I  was a member Co-op from the west coast that supplied many HQ west  coast shows,  and like this one, they offered what it truly sounded like sitting in that sweet spot.

This shows takes that experiences and brings it even closer with this matix hybrid.

The first thing  you notice is the closeness you experience to the  music and the richness and clarity of every instrument, including Phil who really shines on this  show and along with Billy  and Mickey who give this entire performance that extra high test octane. 

Then there are the vocals and  you really will thoroughly  enjoy this very strong show.

Yes there are some  blemishes, the  biggest one being the  bridge on He's Gone but they make up for it at the  end with the New Orlean's inspired funeral march.

Set  one is  sharp and fun which are highlighted in just   about  every song with Peggi-O, Wang Dang and Ramble on Rose really standing out.

Set II is all about how they played it as it is very text book, except the Playin'> Eyes, which I was lucky to see 3 times over the years and was  played together less than a dozen maybe?

The sparks really  fly with Estimated which is a tour de-force and the band really soars. Bobby is perfect the entire night driving every song he sings with that assured  passion but not  getting to the point of cheese.

The D/S are  very  fun and this leads into a slithering Spanish  jam that is quite good followed by a strong Other one into a stupendous Wharf Rat>Sugar Magnolia closah!

Sorry I could not resist as Boston was my  home town for 8 years  starting in 1985.

IFTL is played perfect with that 3 minute  spunk that had many heading for the exits but we had  three more shows to go in this  run and  Jerry ended five out of  six these shows on this run and would play 14 encores total on this tour so who could complain.

Big  kudos to Roger for painstakingly putting this one together, well done brother!

Happy trails
